“Dieting” & “Bulking” aren’t your only options

👉🏻 There’s NOTHING wrong with maintaining what you’ve already achieved

The all-or-nothing mindset — if you’re not in a calorie deficit to lose, you must be gaining weight is false. Spending a considerable time at true maintenance calories is progress and a goal many of us should have.

When you have a lot of weight to lose, DIET BREAKS, from a few days to a few weeks at maintenance calories, are a critical part of successful fat-loss plans. Studies have shown those who take diet breaks lose the same amount of weight, or more, as those who continuously diet 🤗 (PMID: 28925405)

Why? Diet breaks cut up the monotony. More food will feel better, improve workout performance, help reverse any metabolic adaptations, and help you mentally when you’re ready to get back to losing. And, the more practice you have MAINTAINING your weight, the better off you‘ll be when you hit your final goal 🙌🏻
.

RECIPE‼️ 75% less calories & 90% less sugar than store-bought! 🙌🏻

Cranberry sauce is one of my favorite Holiday dinner side dishes. Traditional recipes have 110 calories & 22g sugar per 1/2 cup. This has just a fraction of that with ALL the sweet & tart cranberry flavor 😋

🍽️ Makes 7 servings, each:
29 calories, 0g fat, 27.5g carbs (2g fiber, 3.5g sugar), 0g protein

❇️ Ingredients
* 12oz. (340g) fresh cranberries
* 3/4 cup (144g) @swervesweetie granular sugar substitute 
* 1/2 cup (120mL) water 
* 1/2 cup (120ml) reduced-sugar orange juice
* Cinnamon and salt to taste

Optional add-ins: raisins or blueberries for added sweetness, nutmeg, allspice. If adding spices, start with a pinch of each and add more to your taste.

✳️ Directions:
1. Add water, juice, and sugar to a stovetop pan over high heat and bring to a boil. Stir to dissolve the sugar.
2. Add the cranberries to the pot and return to a boil. Lower the heat and simmer for 10-15 minutes or until most of the cranberries have burst.
3. Remove the pot from heat and add cinnamon and salt. Let cool completely to room temperature, then transfer to a bowl to chill in the refrigerator. 
4. Let it sit in the fridge for atleast two hours to cool and thicken. 

Note: Swerve contains undigestable carbs, which is why it’s considered calorie free.

ENJOY!

Success OR failure with your fitness goals can snowball. You can add up small wins that turn into big wins- OR- you can have a minor setback which turns cumulates major setbacks, which could lead to giving up your goals altogether.

Here’s whats important to remember:

You aren’t a robot where a set of actions will produce a predictable output. Instead, you can influence your body through diet and exercise, but HOW it changes isn’t entirely predictable or under your control.

This is why it’s helpful to FOCUS ON THE PROCESS 
and what you can control to keep moving forward when you think change isn’t happening (or happening fast enough). For example:

▫️How often will you go to the gym?
▫️How much protein or veggies will you eat?
▫️How much sleep will you try to get?

👆🏼The details of the process will vary based on your life circumstances, what’s sustainable, and your desired outcome (i.e. not everyone has the same amount of time to work out, or needs the same amount of food).

You also need to EMBRACE “GOOD ENOUGH”

Most of the time, “failures” are a perspective that can be reframed more positively.

Let’s say you don’t have time for a full workout so you get down on yourself and count it as a failure. On the flip side, you might be able to squeeze in 10-15 minutes of a workout at home. 

👆🏼You can take this as a small win and/or learn something that will help when you face future setbacks. You only fail when you decide what a failure is.

Consistency is key. Control what you can. Learn from mistakes. Something small always better than having done nothing at all ♥️.

But the importance of protein holds true!

If you’re active and wish to build muscle or lose fat: 0.8-1 gram of protein per pound you weigh every day is a fantastic goal 🍳. The leaner, older, and more active you are, the more protein you will benefit from.

Not only does this support a lean, strong body, but it improves satiety, increases overall calorie expenditure, supports recovery from exercise, and improves bone density.

If planning your days’ food around this feels overwhelming, try aiming for 30 grams 4x’s daily, and build your meals around your favorite protein sources. Here are some examples:

🍗4oz. Roasted turkey breast 34g

💀🔥Try this if:

1. You work out at home with a limited weight selection
2. You’ve plateaued in weight for a particular move
3. You can’t find the set of weights you NEED in the gym 😩

You can fatigue your muscles with lighter weights to trigger a growth response by slowing the eccentric of a lift (lowering the weight) to 3-5 seconds. 

The eccentric phase is when the majority of muscle fiber damage occurs. Controlling and slowing the negative portion of a rep will help improve your mind-to-muscle connection and add time under tension to force your muscles to adapt, strengthen, and grow.

💪🏼 To blast a strength plateau: add a few slow eccentrics at the end of your sets. If the goal is 12 reps, slow down the last 3.
💪🏼 To increase the intensity of lighter weights: add as many slow eccentric reps needed so the last 2-3 reps of your set feel challenging. 
💪🏼 You can also add reps in these scenarios. At the point you can perform 15-20 reps in a set, increasing weight is a better, more time-efficient option.

I hope this helps! Happy lifting 💪🏼

💪🏼 Let me make my case:

The most admired female physiques these days tend to be significantly more muscular than the average?

With the growth of women resistance training, I get surprised when I hear a comments over lifting and getting “bulky.” I hope this will clear the doubts you may have:

With 1/10th of men’s testosterone, muscle is tough for women to build. This is especially true for women who are older and/or dieting.

Any muscle you gain is acquired VERY gradually – there will always be plenty of time to apply the brakes if you feel you’re becoming too muscular.

In my experience, most women find when they do build new muscle, and they like it much more than they imagined 🥳

But if they end up not liking it, no problem! It’s very easy to lose 😫

Muscle is actually what gets and keeps you lean. If a man and woman are matched for body weight, the man can likely eat more than the woman without fat gain consequence. Differences in muscle mass makes a significant difference.

Here’s how muscle boosts your metabolic rate:
1. The training required to build muscle requires energy, both to perform and to recover from.
2. Once built, this new muscle requires you to expend additional energy daily to maintain it.
3. The body produces glucose from carbohydrates, it’s preferred energy source. Glucose is stored in your muscles for future use. The more muscle you have, the more storage capacity of glucose there is. This means you can eat more carbs before they are potentially stored as fat (in a calorie surplus) 🥯
4. When you have more muscle, activities that once seemed hard are easier to perform, making it likely you’ll do it more, which expends energy.

Lifting iron regularly is your best friend. If you’re not convinced, give it a go and prove me wrong 😉

Assuming fat loss is your primary goal, it is in your best interest to maximize these three pre-requisites before you decide which podcast or Netflix series will fill your time on the elliptical:

1️⃣ Nutrition influences around 80% of your results. Daily calorie and protein intake are essential. How much of each you need is unique to you and your goal.

2️⃣ Strength Training tells your body you NEED your muscle. Muscle catabolism is more likely to occur in a calorie deficit without strength training and sufficient protein.

3️⃣ Sleep keeps your stress and cortisol levels in check and improves recovery and hunger levels.

There’s no doubt that all three are easier said than done. 👉🏻 Create awareness, practice daily, and do your best.

When adding cardio to your plan, consider these:

✨How much cardio should you do?
If you live a more sedentary lifestyle (office job, driver), including cardio in your daily routine will likely improve your overall health, decrease stress, and help create your calorie deficit. However, if you work a labor-intensive job and your daily activity levels are high (housekeeper, landscaper, server), additional cardio might not be necessary.

✨What kind of cardio should you do?
It’s a common misconception that cardio is only effective when performed at high intensity; you’re out of breath and super sweaty. Thankfully, you don’t need to run a marathon to reap the benefits—activities like cleaning, shopping, gardening, shoveling snow, or washing your car count. If you’re active and your heart rate is slightly elevated, you’re doing cardio! While HIIT may be more time-efficient and less boring, it tends to be harder to recover from, so you can’t do it as often as low-intensity cardio. One to two sessions per week is likely plenty. My suggestion is to find the mode you enjoy 👍🏼

🍨 Casein Protein Ice Cream // 137 calories + 26.5g protein 💪🏼

Protein ingestion following resistance training stimulates muscle protein synthesis (MPS). The MPS response to a single lifting session extends well beyond the first couple of hours of exercise recovery, and studies have shown that a more even distribution of protein throughout the day yields higher MPS and recovery rates. 

A recent study investigated the effects of 40g of casein protein before sleep on exercise performance recovery after professional soccer players played a match in the evening. When compared to a carbohydrate placebo, they saw:

1️⃣ 22% higher MPS rates 
2️⃣ Counter-movement jump performance return to baseline 36 hours vs. 60+ hours post-match
3️⃣ Reduced muscle soreness

These results are significant considering the soccer players already consumed a post-game protein meal (0.5g/kg body weight) and followed a consistently high protein diet (~1.9g/kg or 0.9g/lb bodyweight).
(PMID: 30204517)

Simply put, overnight MPS rates are limited to amino acid availability. Casein protein before sleep increases available amino acids and might be the boost you need to enhance muscle gain & strength further 💪🏼

How many calories do I eat? I get this question a lot 😏

▫️April 2022: dieting ~1300 calories during the last few weeks leading up to my show. I was doing 5-6 days of weights + 30-45 minutes of cardio.
▫️April 2023: building ~1700 calories over the coming weeks before dieting for my next competition. 5 days of weights + some cardio. These numbers have been more loosely tracked as well.

☝🏻What's important to know is how much I eat in both scenarios is irrelevant to YOU and your goals.

Even if we are the same height, weight, age, and gender, it’s doubtful we would need the same amount of food daily to maintain our body weight. Our daily calorie requirements are unique and become moving targets by things like:

▫️Occupation (active vs. sedentary)
▫️Weekly training frequency & level of intensity
▫️Recent history of weight loss (metabolic adaptation)
▫️Daily non-exercise activity levels (NEAT)
▫️Diet quality + thermic effect of food (whole foods & lots of protein vs. highly-processed little protein)
▫️Overall health (thyroid & other hormones) and level of muscularity

Also, what you view as "a lot" or “very few” calories is highly subjective. Everyone has a different threshold of energy on which they thrive. So, rather than comparing my numbers to yours, you have to apply your numbers and observe what happens:

1️⃣ Track your food intake, and note your NEAT levels, frequency and intensity of exercise, quality of your diet, quality of sleep, and the like.

2️⃣Use this data to identify what's working based on how your body responds over the next four weeks. Consistency is key! 

3️⃣ Over the coming months, you will learn SO much about YOUR body and have a good idea how many calories YOU need to achieve YOUR goals 🙌🏼

Make sense?

The point is that there is a place in fitness (and the weight room 😉) for everyone and every goal 🎯. When times get tough, and motivation is low, your why should keep you returning.

🥩🍳🥓 Did you know eating protein stimulates muscle protein synthesis (MPS) by providing amino acids to your muscles?

The degree of MPS is primarily determined by protein type (🥩complete vs. 🥦 incomplete), how much protein you have, and how old you are.

Here are a few things to consider:

1️⃣ The current Recommended Daily Allowance (RDA) of 0.8g per kilogram of body weight is defined as the BARE MINIMUM to exist, not improve body composition.

2️⃣ The older you get, the more protein you may need. A recent study in The Journal of Nutrition showed a ~10% reduction in protein digestion + absorption in older (66-76) versus younger (19-25) individuals. A low-protein diet combined with a sedentary lifestyle likely leads to Sarcopenia or age-related muscle loss.

3️⃣ Animal protein sources include all nine essential amino acids (EAA) we NEED from food, while most plant-based sources are missing a few. Eat a variety of proteins to fill possible gaps, especially where the EAA Leucine is concerned.

4️⃣ Small meals with little protein or low leucine content may be inadequate for MPS. ~0.05g of leucine per kg body weight is estimated to maximize MPS. If you weigh 125 pounds, that’s 2.5g of leucine = ~23g serving of whey isolate, 31g soy isolate, or 142g of chicken.

5️⃣ Only those with pre-existing kidney issues should be cautious of higher protein diets.

👈🏼 SWIPE to see a day of food for me -- every day looks different. I shoot for at least 140g per day. I have been eating this way for so long it's HARD not to hit that number. I promise it’s possible!! 

What YOU eat should be optimized for YOUR goals, stats, and food preferences. There is no one size fits all.

How accurate is your home scale? I share my results versus a recent Dexa scan here!

Some background info:

1. A DEXA body composition scan, which stands for dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry, passes two very low-dose X-ray beams, with differing energy levels, through the body’s tissues. It provides measures and information on the specific distribution of lean muscle, fat, water, and bone within the body.

2. Your home scale uses Bioelectrical Impedance Analysis (BIA) and uses resistance to flow of an electrical current sent through the body to estimate total body water. This can then be used to assess general body fat. It cannot provide exact distribution.

Genetics and hormones control where your body fat is stored. Knowing your specific body fat distribution matters because it can significantly impact your health. Excess fat around the abdomen, in particular, has been linked to a higher risk of health problems such as heart disease, diabetes, and stroke.

Every bodyfat measuring tool has a margin of error. Based on what I could find, error rates hover around 3% for Dexa scans and 8% for home scales that use BIA. 

One study published by J. Funct. Morphol. Kinesiol in 2019 showed BIA underestimated fat mass and percentage of body fat and overestimated fat-free mass compared to the DXA. However, when assessing the change in fat mass over time, there were no statistically significant differences between the BIA vs. DEXA. 

Therefore, when tracking body composition over time, your home scale should do a decent job of showing trends and changes, although the numbers aren’t going to be 100% accurate.

Be sure to use your scale at the same time of day and under the same conditions. Differences between whether you’ve eaten or worked out before using your scale will impact results.

There’s NO limit of protein that can be absorbed by the body. If you eat it, you absorb it. Just not all of it will be used for building muscle (Muscle Protein Synthesis, or MPS) 💪🏻

When we eat protein it gets broken down to it’s building blocks called amino acids. These amino acids are used for MANY things in the body, like MPS, the production of skin, hair, nails, blood, hormones, enzymes, organs, etc.

Friendly reminder: YOU DID NOT FAIL your workout today! These things are not indicators of a good workout:

⏳ WORKOUT LENGTH
The best workouts have quality movements, challenging weight selection, quality reps, and intent. Maybe that takes you 45 min, perhaps 2 hours. Remember that rest periods between sets are super important too! They help you lift as much weight on your last set as on your first set.

🔥CALORIES BURNED
First, calorie trackers are notoriously inaccurate! Your diet is the best place to lead your calorie deficit, followed by daily movement (NEAT), then cardio 🤗. Second, the purpose of your resistance training plan is muscle building/retention. Building muscle burns calories, and more muscle means more calories are also burned at rest.

💦 HOW MUCH YOU SWEAT
There are so many factors involved in how much you sweat. Climate, genetics, and clothing are all factors here. Think about how much you can sweat sitting in the sun on a hot summer day versus how little you can sweat sprinting outside on a cold winter day.

😩 HOW SORE YOU ARE
While soreness might feel debilitating when your first start resistance training, the more you train, the better your body adapts. This is called the repeated bout effect. Therefore, if you aren’t getting as sore as you used to, that doesn’t mean you aren’t pushing yourself hard enough. Your body is adapting to stress, which is normal and GOOD!! This may change with new stimuli, different recovery strategies, nutrition/hydration status, etc. Conversely, too much soreness could hinder your workouts and hold you back from one of the most essential rules for muscle growth: progressive overload.

If you’re getting stronger, improving your form and range of motion, feeling more confident, sexy, and powerful- these are great indicators your workouts are working 🙌🏻

⚠️Reminder: a STAGE body & REAL body are two separate things (here’s why 👇🏻)

Most fitness competitors apply some variation of a ‘peak week’ nutrition plan by manipulating carbohydrates, water, and/or sodium.

The purpose is to maximize muscle glycogen content (carbohydrate storage), minimize subcutaneous water, and reduce the risk of bloating to bring about a more aesthetically pleasing physique.

Here’s what the first few days looks like for me:

▫️Carbs are under 100g/day for the first five days. As you can see I’ve placed most in pre/post-workout meals for performance and recovery.

▫️Reducing carbs initially reduces muscle glycogen and water storage. This also means scale weight will be down. I lost one pound in one day, remember this next time your carb intake varies greatly 😉

▫️ Water intake is also up to encourage my body to hold onto LESS water 💦

▫️This will be followed by ultra-high-carb days to overload the muscles with glycogen and water. 

▫️Sodium + water intake are also reduced closer to show date to minimize subcutaneous water and  maximize muscle definition.

Studies are limited but a have shown glycogen loading can increase intracellular water content, muscle thickness, and lean body mass (exact outcomes vary). Further, those who manipulated carb intake displayed visual improvements based on photos shown to judges*

The extent of these types of nutrition manipulation strategies varies and necessary to remain competitive. However, they are applied short-term and not part of a healthy lifestyle.

I think it’s super fascinating and serves as a good reminder NEVER to compare yourself to anyone else ❤️
.
.
.
*Escalante, G., Stevenson, S.W., Barakat, C. et al.Peak week recommendations for bodybuilders: an evidence based approach. BMC Sports Sci Med Rehabil 13, 68 (2021).

Most of your glute training can be separated into the upper (hip thrust) and lower (hip hinge) movements. There are various ways to target each, so here are some examples.

Muscle takes time to build, so you might see noticeable changes within 10-12 weeks based on diet, training, training experience, and body fat levels. FACT: You can have your 🍰 + eat it too 😋

Losing fat + building muscle really isn’t complicated. Here are four things I wish I knew sooner:

1️⃣ Fasted cardio is not superior for fat-loss. If you perform better fed, you’ll get more out of your workouts - that’s the best path for YOU.

2️⃣ There is no perfect macro ratio 🍗🍞🥑. Your protein, carb, and fat needs vary based on your goal, calorie needs, body weight / composition, and food preferences. Protein intake is fairly fixed and based on body weight, while carb and fat ratios change based on your calorie needs.

3️⃣ Carbs 🍇🥞🥪🧇 are not inherently fattening. They’re actually harder for your body to convert to body fat than fat itself. The right carbs will actually improve your fat loss + muscle gain efforts.

4️⃣ When you eat doesn't matter much for fat loss or gain either. Early breakfast, late dinner, and snacks in between are ok. However, protein distribution throughout the day can be beneficial for muscle gain 💪🏻

Lifting is not cardio. Let’s not confuse the two. The goal when lifting is NOT calorie burn, but to get stronger and build muscle. If sweat and calorie burn are the reasons you lift, it’s probably time to shift your mindset around exercise and food.

I promise if you embrace these five things, you’ll transform your body forever 🔥 

1. Train hard (1-2 reps shy of failure)
2. Rest between sets (recover)
3. Eat enough protein (0.8-1g/lb body weight)
4. Eat enough calories (~10% deficit to ~10% surplus)
5. Do 1-4 for at least a year (be consistent)

You must to FORCE your muscles to grow 💪🏻

And I’m willing to bet you’re much stronger than you give yourself credit. How do you know you’re close to failure? Pick a safe exercise, like a bicep curl or tricep extension, and go to it! How many more reps could you do beyond your set with decent form? If it’s consistently more than 4-5, it’s time to bump up your weight a bit.

Rest periods are often misunderstood 🦋

Rest allows you to recover between sets so you can lift heavier, work HARDER, and get the absolute most out of your next set. Lack of rest actually contributes to higher fatigue and doing LESS in the gym. One minute between sets is a good approach, but if you need more, take it!

Gym efforts need to be matched in the kitchen 🍳

Sufficient protein and calories are required to grow, plain and simple. How much of each is unique to you and depends on things like body fat percentage, training experience, and age. The guidelines above are a great range to shoot for daily.

Be consistent with all of the above for ONE YEAR ⏳

Building muscle and changing your body composition is a slow process. Consistency is 🔑!! So be patient and allow the magic to happen.

⚠️ Stop doing this on your fat-loss journey!

The fat-loss component of your plan should be covered primarily by establishing a calorie deficit through diet. Cardio is often a great tool to help you reach a calorie deficit so you don’t have to cut calories excessively. 

It’s also important to know the “calorie burn” shown on your wearable or cardio machine is notoriously inaccurate. Stanford Medicine researchers who tested seven commercial fitness tracking devices under a variety of conditions found that NONE of them measured calories burned accurately. The most accurate device was off by around 27%, and the least accurate was off by 93% 😳

How much cardio?

There is no definite rule on how much cardio you should do. Since cardio has benefits beyond fat loss, consider your lifestyle and daily activity levels to determine how much and what kind of cardio is best for you. 

If you live a more sedentary lifestyle (office job, driver), including cardio in your daily routine will likely improve your overall health and decrease stress while helping you create your calorie deficit. 

If you work a labor-intensive job and your daily activity levels are high (housekeeper, landscaper, restaurant server), additional cardio might not be necessary.

When to do cardio?

There is a good amount of research that suggests the time of day, fed, or fasted cardio will not provide any additional benefits or drawbacks in terms of overall fat loss. With this in mind, it’s still best to do cardio after weights so you’re as strong as possible to maximize the results of your resistance training routine. Otherwise, don’t overthink it 🙏🏼

The best plan you can choose is whichever fits your life and is enjoyable, so you stick to it without quitting prematurely.

If you find that getting your cardio done first thing in the morning OR after work is best for you, do that! It can also be as simple as using the stairs over the elevator in your apartment or office building or doing 30 minutes of cycling after every upper body day.

Focus on creating a plan that’s as enjoyable as possible for YOU so you stick to it 💪🏼

Elevate your glutes + booty gains with the Smith Machine Frog Pump 🐸🍑!!

1️⃣ Slide an incline bench, set around 50-60 degrees, under the Smith Machine with the bar + pad slightly higher than hip height.

2️⃣ Position yourself on the bench with hips under the bar and feet together on the edge of the bench to form a froggy position.

3️⃣ Engage your core, keep your upper back pinned to the bench, and lift your hips under the bar to unhook it. Squeeze your glutes at the top. This is your starting position.

4️⃣ Keeping your core engaged, hinge at the hips to lower them into the crease of the bench. Keep tension on the glutes by not letting them touch the bench. 

5️⃣ Return to the starting position and SQUEEZE your glutes hard at the top. Repeat for reps and sets, focusing on the mind-muscle connection with your glutes.

6️⃣ Gradually increase the weight as you master your form and strength improves.

Ladies: lift like you want to get “BULKY”— because this is scary 🫣👇🏻

Muscle loss can affect anyone, but is more common in aging women:

▫️After 30, women tend to lose 3-5% muscle and strength every decade
▫️After 50, muscle and strength loss can increase to 1-2% per year
▫️By 70, ~25% of a woman’s muscle and strength can be gone 😳
PMID: 15192443
▫️50% of older women with muscle loss struggle getting out of a chair, walking, and other basic activities of daily life 💔. PMID: 33489646

At the cognitive health level, regular engagement in exercise in midlife is also associated with decreased risk of dementia later in life. PMID: 26061528

Studies have shown hypertrophy-based resistance training provides the necessary stimulus to increase BDNF, or brain-derived neurotrophic factor. BDNF helps your brain, maintain proper connections so you can learn and remember new things— another vital attribute for healthy and happy aging. PMID: 28511848

I watched my dad’s mental and physical decline from Alzheimers over a 10-year span, so this is a HUGE motivator for me ♥️

So, if you’re scared of getting “bulky” today, take a peek inside a nursing home. I guarantee what you see there is a hell of a lot scarier!

Build it now BEFORE it’s gone. It's never too late, and your future self will thank you 🫶🏼

🏋🏼‍♀️Engage in regular exercise, including resistance training, to maintain muscle and strength.

🍗Eat good protein sources from lean meats, eggs, and beans. The older we get, the less efficient our bodies are at building muscle from the amino acids we eat. Aim for at least 25-30 grams of protein at every meal. 

🥛 If your diet falls short in Omega-3’s, Calcium and Vitamin D, consider supplementation.

👇🏻 Gingerbread Cookie RECIPE // 85 Cal + 7g P!

✅ SO good and easy to make. I got 12, each: Cal: 85, F: 3g, C: 8g (fiber 1g, sugar 3g), P: 7g 👏🏻

🧡Gingerbread Cookies:
* 2 scoops (62g) vanilla protein powder (I used @questnutrition )
* 3/4 cup (95g) @kodiakcakes Buttermilk flapjack & waffle mix
* 1 tsp (2g) ground ginger
* 1 tsp (2g) cinnamon
* 1/4 tsp (<1g) nutmeg
* 1/4 tsp (<1g) baking soda
* 1/4 cup (48g) @swervesweetie brown sugar substitute
* 1/4 cup (56g) light butter (room temp)
* 2 tbsp (30mL) molasses
* 2 tbsp (30mL) sugar-free maple syrup
🤍Frosting:
* 1 tbsp (14g) coconut oil 
* 1/2 scoop (15g) vanilla protein powder
* 1 tbsp (15mL) unsweetened almond milk, or to consistency 

🥣Directions:
▫️In a large bowl whisk together the dry cookie ingredients. Add wet ingredients, mix, and knead to form your dough. If it’s too sticky, add a little protein powder or Kodiak Cakes mix.
▫️Cover and refrigerate for one hour. The cooler the dough is, the easier it will be to work with!
▫️Preheat oven to 325°F + line a baking sheet with parchment paper/silicone mat.
▫️Place dough between parchment paper and use a rolling pin to flatten around 1/8” thick. Cut cookies using a cutter, peel away excess dough, and carefully place onto your baking sheet. The thinner they are, the more delicate they will be.
▫️Roll scraps into a ball and repeat. I spread the last bit of dough inside the cutter to form the last cookie. I got 12 cookies, but that may vary based on the thickness of your dough and shape of your cookies. 
▫️Bake for 12 minutes, or until cookies are soft and golden. They will firm as they cool. Completely cool before frosting. 
▫️Melt coconut oil in the microwave, ~15-20 seconds, then mix in the protein powder for a sand-like mixture. Add milk in small increments until a thick, but spreadable frosting is reached, ~1 tbsp.
▫️Cut a small hole in one corner of a zip-lock baggie and squeeze frosting through to decorate.
▫️Refrigerate cookies for ~20 minutes for the frosting to firm. 

Enjoy!

QUESTION for you 👇🏻

Are people who successfully have a mentally + physically healthy relationship with food a slave to clean, organic, “good” food? Do they keep a list of “bad” foods?

Nope, and neither should you.

Food is neither clean and pure 😇 nor evil 😈. 

Food is neutral, and eating a nutritious diet involves variety 🍠🍳🥦🍕🥂

It’s not realistic or necessary to restrict every “bad” food all the time. My goal is to share real-life solutions for busy schedules, picky eaters, and those who have zero desire to give up pizza, pancakes, bubbles 🥂or shop at Whole Foods regularly 🤑 — I certainly don’t! 

I’m not saying that you shouldn’t care about what you put in your body. Every single food item lies on a LARGE spectrum of nutritional value, and there are a lot more practical and informative considerations about what you choose to eat:

What is nourishing?
What tastes delicious?
What keeps you satisfied?
What keeps you consistent?
What choices best align with your goals?
What options should you have in moderation?
Do you have any medical restrictions?
What does your ENTIRE diet look like?

A diet that is healthy + enjoyable can look different for everyone. So please, ditch the guilt and the shame surrounding nutrition and focus on educating, informing, and living our best life WHILE reaching your health and fitness goals.

🍾 Alcohol isn’t something I’m advocating more of. For me, letting loose every now and then and enjoying a few glasses is a simple treat for my mental health. 

I’m team #moderationnotdeprivation - how about you?

Going out tonight? Check out this handy guide 👉🏼

Most things you eat or drink include calories from fat, carbs, protein, or a combination of those three. Alcohol is the exception and is its own macro!

Alcohol provides 7.1 calories per gram: double that of protein and carbs and slightly below fat🥂🍻🥃

Unlike protein, carbs, and fat, alcohol is non-essential for bodily functions and technically a toxin. This means your body has no storage capacity for alcohol, so it works to metabolize and eliminated it BEFORE any food. One of many reasons why alcohol can hinder our health, fat loss, and muscle gain goals 💪🏽

Alcohol tends to be part of social gatherings, and a healthy social life is an important part of our mental health and quality of life. Therefore, moderation is 🔑. If your health and body composition goal is a top priority, I suggest limiting alcohol intake to two to three drinks per week. Lastly, be sure to track it!

42 years > 20 years 💪🏽 How much muscle do you think I’ve built?

I started lifting around 20 years old. I have no clue what my body composition was or what weights I used for things like squats, bicep curls, and rows 🤷🏼‍♀️

How much you can build in your lifetime isn’t a black-and-white answer. Genetics plays a role, and there will be exceptions to the average in both directions. 

Assuming your plan is optimized for muscle growth:

▫️Intelligent training with enough volume, intensity, and frequency 📶
▫️Good nutrition with enough food and protein 🍗🥩

In the first year, 10-12 pounds.
The second year, maybe another 5 pounds.
The third year could be another 2-4 pounds.
After the fourth year, a couple of pounds per year.

You can expect to near your genetic potential in 8-10 years and about 20-25 pounds of muscle. These numbers are about double for men.

Plus, the older you start, the less muscle you will build. This is because as you age, hormone levels change, your body is less efficient using the amino acids from the protein you eat, and you lose the ability to recruit muscle fibers.

Then, to keep your head-earned muscle, you must train and eat with that intention. Luckily, maintaining is easier than building.

I hope this gives you an idea of the possibilities that lie ahead 💪🏼
